observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

GSO, in coordination with the Internal Audit Office, to formulate a system or flow of procedures for the receipt, issuance, documentation, recording, and inventory taking of in-kind donations, for guidance and uniform application;

MHO and other offices receiving in-kind donations to inform and submit relevant documents to the GSO to acknowledge receipt and conduct inspection of items received;

GSO to forward relevant documents to the Accounting Office to record the receipts and issuances of in-kind donations; and

GSO, MHO and other Implementing Offices to properly use and fill out the RIS, ICS for semi-expendable items, RSMI, and stock cards, and conduct regular monitoring of the donated items.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

Clean and Green Program coordinator to affix her initial in the daily time records and accomplishment reports of the workers to ensure that entries therein were duly monitored and verified, hence, valid; 

Job Order workers to prepare accomplishment reports which are specific as to actual duties performed and deliverables attained to substantiate the payment of wages; 

HRMO to include the actual schedule of work and places of assignment of the Job Order workers assigned in the Clean and Green Program to justify actual necessity; and

Program proponent to reassess the need for hiring 90 JO workers to perform the repeated daily tasks mentioned herein.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:

The Municipal Health Officer to ensure that lists of individuals quarantined in the isolation facility are completely filled out, and duly approved to facilitate verification;

Heads of offices who prepare training proposals to conduct seminars and workshops in available rooms within premises or avail of government facilities, on a non-residential basis, to save on training expenses;

Requesting officers and the BAC Chairman to include a clause in the contracts that payments for meals will be based on the actual number of event attendees/meal recipients;

Requesting officers and the BAC Chairman to ensure that Purchase Requests and Requests for Quotations for meals are duly supported with food specifications, and 

Heads of offices who prepare training proposals to ensure that participants thereto are employees whose development and productivity will benefit the LGU in the long-term.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:
The Municipal Health Officer to ensure that lists of individuals quarantined in the isolation facility are completely filled out, and duly approved to facilitate verification;
Heads of offices who prepare training proposals to conduct seminars and workshops in available rooms within premises or avail of government facilities, on a non-residential basis, to save on training expenses;
Requesting officers and the BAC Chairman to include a clause in the contracts that payments for meals will be based on the actual number of event attendees/meal recipients;
Requesting officers and the BAC Chairman to ensure that Purchase Requests and Requests for Quotations for meals are duly supported with food specifications, and
Heads of offices who prepare training proposals to ensure that participants thereto are employees whose development and productivity will benefit the LGU in the long-term.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to Management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2023-004 dated March 1, 2023.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct concerned officials and employees to:

Submit an explanation on the procurement of COVID-19 test kits that were not supported with the FDA Special Certification and results of the mandatory performance testing by the RITM as required by FDA Memoranda Nos. 2020-011 and 2020-022. Henceforth, procurement of the test kits should be duly supported with the requisite documents;

Submit a justification on the non-posting of the Notices of Award and purchase orders in the GPPB online portal for procurements undertaken under the Negotiated Procurement-Emergency Cases modality;

Henceforth, ensure that Purchase Requests for the procurement of COVID-19 test kits contain detailed technical description/specification to ensure that items delivered conform with the needs of the LGU; and

Submit the necessary documents to validate the distribution of the COVID-19 test kits amounting to ₱735,500.00. Henceforth, the issuances of test kits should be duly accounted and properly documented to justify the recording thereof as expenses.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct concerned officials and employees to:

Submit a justification on the above-listed deficiencies;

Ensure that Purchase Requests and Requests for Quotations for meals are duly supported with food specifications and payments for meals are based on the actual number of event attendees/meal recipients;

Comply with the posting requirements in GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020;

Submit Purchase Orders within the prescribed period, and the Acceptance and Inspection Reports of consumable and perishable items to this Office within 24 hours from acceptance of the items delivered;

Submit a certified list approved and noted by the Municipal Health Officer of the individuals who spent New Year’s Eve at the quarantine facilities, for verification; and


Submit duly approved office orders of LGU employees and other personnel assigned at the quarantine facilities and checkpoints.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Henceforth, require the Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption thereof as expense, in accordance with the GAM for LGUs, Volume I;

Direct the concerned officials and employees to submit the Requisition and Issue Slips and Relief Distribution Sheets indicating actual issuance and distribution of the welfare goods.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the BAC or duly authorized procuring unit to:

Provide justification as to the payments made to the supplier despite its failure to provide the OSS in the prescribed format as per GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 and the absence of the required recommendation to award the contract and the corresponding NOA;

Provide an explanation as to the absence of a contract in the proper format, which should include the budgetary allotments and maximum quantity of items or services that was awarded to the supplier, the duration of the agreement and the required warranty clause set forth in GPPB Circular No. 01-2020;

Submit a duly certified list of LSIs/ROFWs who were prescribed by the Rural Health Unit (RHU) to complete their quarantine period in the hotel and the names and office orders of LGU personnel assigned to oversee said individuals, in specific periods; and

Be cognizant of the effectivity dates of Bayanihan Acts One and Two and henceforth comply with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 in the conduct of its procurements for lease of venues to serve as quarantine facilities in the calendar year 2021.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Justify why the payment for consultancy services shall not be disallowed in audit despite the duplication of functions with the legal advisor, and for failure of the technical consultant to comply with the documentary requirement mandated by R.A. No. 9184;

Adopt written policy/procedure/guidelines in hiring consultants with a clearly defined scope of work;




Seek the services of the Provincial Legal Officer or Provincial Prosecutor in the absence of the Municipal Legal Officer to provide necessary legal services, including representation in court; and

Consider the knowledge, training, competence and expertise in the appointment or selection of employees to compose the Bids and Awards Committee and send staff involved in procurement to trainings on R.A. No. 9184 instead of hiring a consultant to provide technical services to the BAC.

We recommend the following:

1. That the MSWD Officer should be designated and bonded as Special Collecting Officer;

2. As such, she shall be subject to Cash Examination;

3. An Official Receipt should be issued immediately upon receipt of payment;

4. Remit the amount of ₱66,050.00 to the Municipal Treasurer;

5. Cause the proper accounting of transactions relative thereto;

6. Intensify collection effort especially on overdue accounts.

